Define the **effective diffusion time**

\[
\tau \;=\;2Dt\qquad\Longleftrightarrow\qquad t=\frac{\tau}{2D}.
\]

Because the prefactor in the local–dimension formula is \(2tD\), this substitution collapses it to \(\tau\):

\[
\boxed{\;
\alpha(x)
  \;=\;
  d
  +\lim_{\tau\to0}\;
      \tau\,
      \frac{\displaystyle\Delta\,
            \rho\!\bigl(x,\tfrac{\tau}{2D}\bigr)}
           {\displaystyle\rho\!\bigl(x,\tfrac{\tau}{2D}\bigr)}
  \;}
\]

If you write \(\rho_\tau(x):=\rho\!\bigl(x,\tfrac{\tau}{2D}\bigr)\), the expression is even cleaner:

\[
\boxed{\;
\alpha(x)=d+\lim_{\tau\to0}\tau\,
          \frac{\Delta\rho_\tau(x)}{\rho_\tau(x)}\;}
\]

Now the limit is taken with respect to the single scale \(\tau\)—the Gaussian variance that regularises the measure—making explicit that the result is independent of the particular value of \(D\) once \(\tau\) is fixed.

